{"actual_usd":0.157765,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":133,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I don't think it works automatically like that.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a second, wanting to say it plain without turning it into a sermon.* \"Christ's death is sufficient for everyone, yeah—but Scripture keeps talking as if people can really refuse Him, and that refusal matters.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"So I'd put it like this: the gift is truly offered, not universally received. If somebody rejects Him, the tragedy isn't that the Cross was too small. It's that grace can be resisted. Are you asking from the angle of universalism, or from worry about somebody specific?\"","rolling_24h_usd":58.078610000000026,"run_id":"350422ea-defb-4e3f-ab09-cad821357da6"}
